{"title_page": "Felipe Andreoli (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Felipe Andreoli\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Luiz Felipe Guimar\u00e3es Andreoli<ref name='andreoli'>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museudatv.com.br/biografias/Felipe%20Andreoli.htm|title=Perfil Felipe Andreoli|author=Museu da TV|date=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426001341/http://www.museudatv.com.br/biografias/Felipe%20Andreoli.htm|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1980|2|5}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo|SP]]  \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Brazilian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Journalist]] and [[humorist]]\n| website     = http://www.felipeandreoli.net\n}}\n'''Luiz Felipe Guimar\u00e3es Andreoli'''<ref name='andreoli'/> ([[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], February 5, 1980) is a Brazilian [[journalist]] and [[humorist]]. Fez parte do programa ''[[Custe o Que Custar]]'', on the [[Rede Bandeirantes]] network,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.band.com.br/tv/noticia/?id=73648|title=Custe o Que Custar estr\u00e9ia dia 17, na Band. N\u00e3o perca!|accessdate=November 6, 2011|author=Assessoria de Imprensa/Band|date=March 12, 2008|publisher=eBand}}</ref> also presenting Band's new sports show, ''Deu Ol\u00e9''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.felipeandreoli.net}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{IMDb name|2316934|Felipe Andreoli}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreoli, Felipe}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male comedians]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Felipe Andreoli\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Luiz Felipe Guimar\u00e3es Andreoli<ref name='andreoli'>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museudatv.com.br/biografias/Felipe%20Andreoli.htm|title=Perfil Felipe Andreoli|author=Museu da TV|date=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426001341/http://www.museudatv.com.br/biografias/Felipe%20Andreoli.htm|archive-date=2012-04-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1980|2|5}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo|SP]]  \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Brazilian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Journalist]] and [[humorist]]\n| website     = http://www.felipeandreoli.net\n}}\n'''Luiz Felipe Guimar\u00e3es Andreoli'''<ref name='andreoli'/> ([[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], February 5, 1980) is a Brazilian [[journalist]] and [[humorist]]. Currently is part of the program ''[[Custe o Que Custar]]'', on the [[Rede Bandeirantes]] network,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.band.com.br/tv/noticia/?id=73648|title=Custe o Que Custar estr\u00e9ia dia 17, na Band. N\u00e3o perca!|accessdate=November 6, 2011|author=Assessoria de Imprensa/Band|date=March 12, 2008|publisher=eBand}}</ref> also presenting Band's new sports show, ''Deu Ol\u00e9''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.felipeandreoli.net}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{IMDb name|2316934|Felipe Andreoli}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreoli, Felipe}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male comedians]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "45.187.145.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felipe_Andreoli_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Clifford McLaglen", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Clifford McLaglen\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name =  \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1892|6|15}}\n| birth_place = [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=y|1978|9|9|1892|6|15}}\n| death_place  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| death_cause   = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Actor]]\n| years_active = 1926\u201336\n}}\n\n'''Clifford McLaglen''' (15 June 1892 \u2013 9 September 1978) was a [[Stepney, London]]-born [[United Kingdom|British]] [[film actor]].<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/individual/10375</ref> He was the brother of several actors including [[Victor McLaglen]], Oscar winner for best actor, ''[[The Informer (1935 film)|The Informer]]'' (director [[John Ford]]), and nominated for best supporting actor ''[[The Quiet Man]]''.\n\nThe other brothers were Leopold McLaglen, wrestler and inventor of a form of [[Jujutsu]] which he taught to the armed forces and police in the old Empire and America; Lewis McLaglen, actor and soldier; Cyril McLaglen, actor and horseman; Arthur McLaglen, actor, unarmed combat professional and sculptor; Kenneth McLaglen, actor and mineralogist; sister Lily Marian McLaglen (Mrs. Lance Tweedy), actress singer and pianist.\n\nClifford McLaglen was born Clifford Henrich McLaglen from Scottish, Irish, and Dutch ancestry. He, like all his brothers except the youngest two, Cyril and Kenneth, served in the [[First World War]]. He also served in the [[Second World War]] going out to Iceland to help guard Sir Winston Churchill, for which he obtained a bulldog and polar bear badge. He also was part of a film unit at that time in the army. His father was born in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]] and came to London to study as Clerk in Orders, eventually becoming Titular Bishop of Claremont in Cape Town but foregoing this to help with the work he dedicated to the helping of poverty stricken children in London and beggars. Lily often helped with this. Clifford worked in a tin mine in [[Cornwall]] before joining up in 1914. Later he worked for Sangers Circus riding horses and doing rope tricks and worked in vaudeville with his various brothers.\n\nHe starred in many silent films in Britain, in ''Boadicea'' (where he rode Roman style learnt in the army and circus); France and Germany, making the reputedly first German Talkie with [[Conrad Veidt]], ''Bride 68'' or ''Das Land Ohne Frauen'', set in Australia with camels and the desert but all filmed in a Berlin studio with a tank of water spilling from overhead and an aeroplane propeller. Clifford also filmed in [[Majorca]], in ''Die Schmugglerbraut von Sorrento'' (various versions changed Majorca to [[Sorrento]]), bringing over horses with him, which he said were seasick. The film was made in Majorca but was meant to be Sorrento. [[Cavalcanti]] made two prize winning films in France with Clifford McLaglen: ''Yvette'' and ''Rien Que Les Heures''. He made a few talkies and was on the stage in America, on Broadway with Frederick Marche's wife Florence Edridge. He was going to make a film called ''Ropes of Sand'' but nothing came of it.\n\nMcLaglen died in [[Huddersfield]], [[Yorkshire]] in 1978.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[In the Blood (1923 film)|In the Blood]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[The Chinese Bungalow (1926 film)|The Chinese Bungalow]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[The White Sheik (1928 film)|The White Sheik]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Boadicea (film)|Boadicea]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Yvette (1928 film)|Yvette]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Struggle for the Matterhorn]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Villa Falconieri (film)|Villa Falconieri]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[The Smuggler's Bride of Mallorca]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Alley Cat (1929 film)|The Alley Cat]]'' (1929)\n*''[[Land Without Women]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Three Kings (film)|The Three Kings]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Lost Patrol (1929 film)|The Lost Patrol]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Bermondsey Kid]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[Late Extra]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[The Mystery of the Mary Celeste]]'' (1935)\nOff the dole (1935) \n* ''[[The Marriage of Corbal]]'' (1936)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0572135}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mclaglen, Clifford}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Clifford McLaglen\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name =  \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1892|6|15}}\n| birth_place = [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=y|1978|9|9|1892|6|15}}\n| death_place  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| death_cause   = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Actor]]\n| years_active = 1926\u201336\n}}\n\n'''Clifford McLaglen''' (15 June 1892 \u2013 9 September 1978) was a [[Stepney, London]]-born [[United Kingdom|British]] [[film actor]].<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/individual/10375</ref> He was the brother of several actors including [[Victor McLaglen]], Oscar winner for best actor, ''[[The Informer (1935 film)|The Informer]]'' (director [[John Ford]]), and nominated for best supporting actor ''[[The Quiet Man]]''.\n\nThe other brothers were Leopold McLaglen, wrestler and inventor of a form of [[Jujutsu]] which he taught to the armed forces and police in the old Empire and America; Lewis McLaglen, actor and soldier; Cyril McLaglen, actor and horseman; Arthur McLaglen, actor, unarmed combat professional and sculptor; Kenneth McLaglen, actor and mineralogist; sister Lily Marian McLaglen (Mrs. Lance Tweedy), actress singer and pianist.\n\nClifford McLaglen was born Clifford Henrich McLaglen from Scottish, Irish, and Dutch ancestry. He, like all his brothers except the youngest two, Cyril and Kenneth, served in the [[First World War]]. He also served in the [[Second World War]] going out to Iceland to help guard Sir Winston Churchill, for which he obtained a bulldog and polar bear badge. He also was part of a film unit at that time in the army. His father was born in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]] and came to London to study as Clerk in Orders, eventually becoming Titular Bishop of Claremont in Cape Town but foregoing this to help with the work he dedicated to the helping of poverty stricken children in London and beggars. Lily often helped with this. Clifford worked in a tin mine in [[Cornwall]] before joining up in 1914. Later he worked for Sangers Circus riding horses and doing rope tricks and worked in vaudeville with his various brothers.\n\nHe starred in many silent films in Britain, in ''Boadicea'' (where he rode Roman style learnt in the army and circus); France and Germany, making the reputedly first German Talkie with [[Conrad Veidt]], ''Bride 68'' or ''Das Land Ohne Frauen'', set in Australia with camels and the desert but all filmed in a Berlin studio with a tank of water spilling from overhead and an aeroplane propeller. Clifford also filmed in [[Majorca]], in ''Die Schmugglerbraut von Sorrento'' (various versions changed Majorca to [[Sorrento]]), bringing over horses with him, which he said were sea sick. The film was made in Majorca but was meant to be Sorrento. [[Cavalcanti]] made two prize winning films in France with Clifford McLaglen: ''Yvette'' and ''Rien Que Les Heures''. He made a few talkies and was on the stage in America, on Broadway with Frederick Marche's wife Florence Edridge. He was going to make a film called ''Ropes of Sand'' but nothing came of it.\n\nMcLaglen died in [[Huddersfield]], [[Yorkshire]] in 1978.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[In the Blood (1923 film)|In the Blood]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[The Chinese Bungalow (1926 film)|The Chinese Bungalow]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[The White Sheik (1928 film)|The White Sheik]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Boadicea (film)|Boadicea]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Yvette (1928 film)|Yvette]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Struggle for the Matterhorn]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Villa Falconieri (film)|Villa Falconieri]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[The Smuggler's Bride of Mallorca]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Alley Cat (1929 film)|The Alley Cat]]'' (1929)\n*''[[Land Without Women]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Three Kings (film)|The Three Kings]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Lost Patrol (1929 film)|The Lost Patrol]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[The Bermondsey Kid]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[Late Extra]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[The Mystery of the Mary Celeste]]'' (1935)\nOff the dole (1935) \n* ''[[The Marriage of Corbal]]'' (1936)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0572135}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mclaglen, Clifford}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Evelina Monzingo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_McLaglen"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)", "text_new": "{{Update|date=October 2015}}\n{{War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present) infobox}}\nThe following items form a partial '''timeline of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]'''. For events prior to October 7, 2001, see [[2001 in Afghanistan]]\n\n==2001==\n\n{{main|2001 in Afghanistan}}\n*October 7: (9 p.m. local time): the United States, supported by [[United Kingdom|Britain]], begins its attack on [[Afghanistan]], launching bombs and cruise missiles against [[Taliban]] military and communications facilities and suspected terrorist training camps. [[Kabul]], [[Kandahar]], and [[Herat]] were hit.\n*October 9: A cruise missile kills four U.N. demining employees and injured four others in a building several miles east of [[Kabul]].\nOctober 19: Airborne invasion into Afghanistan by Rangers of the Third Ranger Battalion Seventy Fifth Ranger Regiment and others seizing a Qandahar airfield named Objective Rhino.\n*October 26: [[Abdul Haq (Afghan leader)|Abdul Haq]] killed.\n*November 6: Zari, Keshendeh and Aq-Kupruk fall to the Northern Alliance<ref name=\"captured\">Independent Online, [http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?sf=522&set_id=1&click_id=3&art_id=qw1005063841541B226 Taliban commander captured in Rebel victory], November 6, 2001</ref>\n*November 8: [[Pakistan]], being the only nation that still had diplomatic ties to the [[Taliban]], asked [[Afghanistan]]'s rulers to close their [[consulate]] in the city of [[Karachi]].\n*November 9: [[Battle of Mazari Sharif]]. \n*November 10: The Taliban and [[Afghan Northern Alliance|Northern Alliance]] fighters both claimed that the strategic northern Afghan city of [[Mazari Sharif]] was taken by Northern Alliance fighters.\n*November 11: Journalists [[Pierre Billaud]], [[Johanne Sutton]], and [[Volker Handloik]] are ambushed and killed.\n*November 12: [[Taliban]] forces abandon [[Kabul]] ahead of advancing [[Afghan Northern Alliance|Northern Alliance]] troops.\n**[[2001 uprising in Herat]].\n*November 14: Northern Alliance fighters took over [[Kabul]], the Afghan capital, and then controlled virtually all the north of Afghanistan.\n*November 16: [[Mohammed Atef]], the military chief of al-Qaeda, killed in a US airstrike.\n*November 19: Four foreign journalists - [[Harry Burton (journalist)|Harry Burton]], [[Maria Grazia Cutuli]], [[Azizullah Haidari]], and [[Julio Fuentes Serrano|Julio Fuentes]] \u2013 were ambushed and killed.\n*November 25: Northern Alliance gained control of [[Kunduz]], the last Taliban stronghold in Northern Afghanistan, but only after Pakistani aircraft rescue several thousand [[Taliban]] and [[Al-Qaeda]] fighters and their military advisers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hersh |first=Seymour M. |url=http://www.newyorker.com/fact/content/articles/020128fa_FACT |title=Annals of National Security: The Getaway |publisher=The New Yorker |date=2009-01-07 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/news/664935.asp?cp1=1 |title=Breaking News, Weather, Business, Health, Entertainment, Sports, Politics, Travel, Science, Technology, Local, US & World News |publisher=msnbc.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051216152224/http://www.msnbc.com/news/664935.asp?cp1=1 |archivedate=December 16, 2005 }}</ref> The Taliban then controlled less than 25% of the country, mainly around Kandahar in the south.\n**U.S. [[United States Marine Corps|Marine]]s landed in force by [[helicopter]] at [[Camp Rhino]] south of [[Kandahar]] and began preparing it for fixed wing aircraft. They also occupied the main road between Kandahar and Pakistan.\n**[[Battle of Qala-i-Jangi]].  Forces loyal to bin Laden smuggled weapons into their prison near Mazar i Sharif after surrendering at Kunduz. They attacked the Northern Alliance guards and storm an armory. [[U.S. Special Forces]] call in air attacks. Hundreds of prisoners are killed as well as 40 Alliance fighters and one U.S. CIA operative, [[Johnny Michael Spann]]. Spann becomes the first U.S. and Coalition combat casualty. A young American named [[John Walker Lindh]] is found in the midst of the rebellion and extradited to the US on terrorism charges.\n*December 6: [[Kandahar]] falls.\n*December: The [[Battle of Tora Bora]] against Taliban and al-Qaeda fighters; [[Osama bin Laden]] reportedly escapes during this battle.\n*December: The [[Dasht-i-Leili massacre]], where hundreds of Taliban were allegedly suffocated to death while being transported in metal containers.\n*December: The [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)|Bonn Agreement]] establishes the postwar system of government for Afghanistan, and establishes the [[International Security Assistance Force]].\n*December 21: The interim Afghan government is sworn in.\n\n==2002==\n{{main|2002 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*January 4: First US soldier dies due to hostile fire.\n*January 24, the [[Hazar Qadam raid]] sees Americans accidentally attack an allied compound collecting weapons for their Karzai government\n*February 14: [[Abdul Rahman (Afghan minister)|Abdul Rahman]], Afghan Aviation and Tourism Minister, killed by angry Hajj pilgrims.\n*March 1: [[Operation Anaconda]] against al-Qaeda fighters launched.\n*April 17: The 87-year-old exiled king of Afghanistan, [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], returns.\n*April 18: [[Tarnak Farm incident]] leaves four Canadians dead from [[friendly fire]].\n*June 11: King Zahir Shah opens the first post-Taliban loya jirga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2038399.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Former king urges Afghan unity |publisher=BBC News |date=2002-06-11 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n*July 1: In [[Uruzgan province]], a US [[AC-130 gunship]] struck a wedding party, killing 48 civilians and injuring 117. The United States claimed their plane had come under attack from anti-aircraft fire before the strike.\n*July 6: Vice President [[Abdul Qadir (Afghan leader)|Abdul Qadir]] assassinated in Kabul.\n*September 5: [[2002 Kabul bombing]] kills 30 people.\n\n==2003==\n{{main|2003 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*August 11 \u2013 NATO officially takes command of peacekeeping in Afghanistan.\n*December 14 \u2013 [[2003 loya jirga]] convened to  consider the proposed [[Constitution of Afghanistan|Afghan Constitution]].\n\n==2004==\n{{main|2004 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*January 4 \u2013 Constitution approved by Loya Jirga.\n*January 26 \u2013 Constitution signed by President Hamid Karzai.\n*October 9 \u2013 [[2004 Afghan presidential election]]. In the country\u2019s first direct election, Hamid Karzai wins the presidency with 55.4% of the vote.\n\n==2005==\n{{main|2005 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*June 28: [[Operation Red Wings]] results in the death of 19 Americans and many Taliban fighters.\n*September 18: [[2005 Afghan parliamentary election]].\n\n==2006==\n{{main|2006 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2006}}\n\n*January 13: [[Damadola airstrike]] by US in Pakistan.\n*February 1: The [[Afghanistan Compact]] is developed, establishing a framework of international cooperation with Afghanistan.\n*March 29: [[Battle of Lashkagar]]. Taliban fighters attack a [[NATO]] base.\n*May 15: [[Operation Mountain Thrust]] is launched, the largest offensive since the fall of the Taliban.\n*July: [[Battle of Panjwaii]] between Canadian NATO forces and the Taliban.\n*September 2: Canadians launch [[Operation Medusa]].\n*September 16: [[Operation Mountain Fury]].\n\n==2007==\n{{main|2007 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2007}}\n\n*February 27: [[2007 Bagram Air Base bombing]] during US Vice President [[Dick Cheney]]\u2019s visit.\n*March 4: [[March 4, 2007 Shooting in Shinwar, Afghanistan|Afghan civilians killed by U.S. troops in Shinwar]].\n*March 6: [[Operation Achilles]] against the Taliban in [[Helmand Province]].\n*May 12: Mullah [[Dadullah]] killed.\n*May 13: [[Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan Skirmishes]].\n*June 15: [[Battle of Chora]] begins.\n*June 28: The [[Hyderabad airstrike]] kills a large number of civilians including women and children.\n*July 19: [[2007 South Korean hostage crisis in Afghanistan]] begins.\n*August 16: [[Nangar Khel massacre]] - Eight civilians including a pregnant women and a baby died when Polish  soldiers shelled the village of Nangar Khel. Seven soldiers have been charged with war crimes.\n*November 6: [[2007 Baghlan sugar factory bombing]] kills 75, including six Afghan MPs.\n*December 7: [[Battle of Musa Qala]], a major clash in Helmand Province.\n\n==2008==\n\n{{main|2008 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2008}}\n*January 14: The [[2008 Kabul Serena Hotel attack]] leaves six people dead.\n*February 17: [[2008 Kandahar bombing]] kills 100 people, the deadliest suicide bombing of the war.\n*June 10: [[Gora Prai airstrike]] in Pakistan kills 11 Pakistani paramilitary troops.\n*June 13: [[Sarposa Prison attack]]. Taliban attack the Sarposa Prison, freeing up to 1,000 prisoners.\n*July 6: [[Deh Bala wedding party bombing]]. 47 civilians mostly women and children killed in Nangarhar province.\n*July 7: The [[2008 Indian embassy bombing in Kabul]] kills 58, including four Indians.  India blames Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] for the attack.\n*July 13: [[Battle of Wanat]]. Taliban fighters attack a NATO base, killing nine American soldiers.\n*August 19: The Taliban kill 10 French soldiers in the [[Uzbin valley ambush]].\n*August 22: [[Azizabad airstrike]] kills up to 90 Afghan civilians.\n*August 27: [[Operation Eagle's Summit]] begins in Helmand Province.\n*September: [[United States-Pakistan skirmishes]].\n*September 3: [[Angoor Ada raid]] by US special forces into Pakistan.\n*November 3: [[Wech Baghtu wedding party attack]] kills 37 civilians mostly women and children.\n*December 19: US vows to send 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan.\n\n==2009==\n{{main|2009 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2009}}\n*February 11: [[February 2009 Kabul raids]]\n*May 4: The [[Granai airstrike]] resulted in one of the highest civilian death tolls from Western military action since foreign forces invaded Afghanistan in 2001.\n*July 2: [[Operation Khanjar]] begins\n*September 4: [[2009 Kunduz airstrike|NATO planes attacks two fuel tankers]], which had been hijacked by Taliban insurgents. Up to 142 people died in the attack, including over 100 Afghan civilian victims.<ref name=spiegel-20100806>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,710439,00.html |title=Germany to Pay $500,000 for Civilian Bombing Victims |author=Matthias Gebauer |publisher=Der Spiegel |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=9 August 2010}}</ref>\n*December 1: U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] announces [[Afghanistan War troop surge of 2009]].\n*December 17: [[Operation Septentrion]], assault by 1100 soldiers (mostly French) in the Uzbin Valley.<ref name=\"BBC2009Dec17\">{{cite web |title=French troops spearhead assault in Afghanistan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8419645.stm |work=BBC News |date=2009-12-17 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC2009Dec18\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8419829.stm |title=French Afghan assault concludes |date=2009-12-18 |accessdate=2012-01-21 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=French troops lead Afghan attack on Taliban |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010535631_apeufranceafghanistan.html |date=2009-12-17 |accessdate=2012-01-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100129051149/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010535631_apeufranceafghanistan.html |archivedate=January 29, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hbKgPKnkMqI0k6GdTP4uP3OTcx9g |author=Karim Talbi |agency=AFP |title=Afghanistan: d\u00e9monstration de force de la L\u00e9gion, cinq Am\u00e9ricains bless\u00e9s |date=2009-12-18 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref>\n*December 29: 10 Afghan civilians mostly school children killed by special operation forces in the botched [[Narang night raid]].\n\n==2010==\n{{main|2010 in Afg\n\n==2011==\n{{main|2011 in Afghanistan}}\n*January 26: The Afghan National Assembly is inaugurated.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/27/world/asia/27afghan.html?partner=rss&emc=rss After Months of Turmoil, Karzai Opens Parliament]</ref>\n*May 1: The number one Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden is killed by U.S. [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEALs]] in Abbottabad, Pakistan, just miles from [[Islamabad]].\n*May 23: 4 U.S. soldiers (2nd Battalion 27th Infantry Regiment) die and 1 wounded following an improvised explosive device attack in Kunar province.\n*June 4\u20136: The Battle Of Gewi Ridge takes place where a platoon of U.S. soldiers air-assaulted the mountain ridge of Gewi (Kunar province) for over-watch of a major re-supply convoy.  Following the insertion, an intensive firefight lasting 52 hours takes place, resulting in the deaths of 50+ Taliban insurgents.\n*August 6: A [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook|CH-47 Chinook]] helicopter transporting 30 U.S. soldiers (including 17 Navy SEALs), 1 civilian interpreter and 7 Afghan troops is shot down in [[Wardak Province]] by [[rocket-propelled grenade|RPG]]-wielding Taliban insurgents. There were no survivors of the crash. This incident marks the deadliest day for U.S. Forces in Afghanistan since the invasion in 2001.\n*August 11: Vengeance is exacted on the 11 Taliban militants involved in downing the CH-47 Chinook, who are killed in an [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16]] airstrike. Meanwhile, five ISAF service members die following an improvised explosive device attack in the southern provinces.\n*December 9: Mohammed Ishmael, Ghaziabad district (Kunar province) police chief is killed in a suicide bombing of a mosque carried out by a 12-year-old Pakistani boy.\n\n==2012==\n{{main|2012 in Afghanistan}}\n\n==2013==\n{{main|2013 in Afghanistan}}\nThe army of the United States continues to conduct missions throughout Afghanistan, began closing forward operating bases (FOB).\n\n==See also==\n*'''2006:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2006]]\n*'''2007:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2007]]\n*'''2008:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2008]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{War in Afghanistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline of the War in Afghanistan (2001-present)}}\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)-related lists]]\n[[Category:Timelines of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|#]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|date=October 2015}}\n{{War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present) infobox}}\nThe following items form a partial '''timeline of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]'''. For events prior to October 7, 2001, see [[2001 in Afghanistan]]\n\n==2001==\n\n{{main|2001 in Afghanistan}}\n*October 7: (9 p.m. local time): the United States, supported by [[United Kingdom|Britain]], begins its attack on [[Afghanistan]], launching bombs and cruise missiles against [[Taliban]] military and communications facilities and suspected terrorist training camps. [[Kabul]], [[Kandahar]], and [[Herat]] were hit.\n*October 9: A cruise missile kills four U.N. demining employees and injured four others in a building several miles east of [[Kabul]].\nOctober 19: Airborne invasion into Afghanistan by Rangers of the Third Ranger Battalion Seventy Fifth Ranger Regiment and others seizing a Qandahar airfield named Objective Rhino.\n*October 26: [[Abdul Haq (Afghan leader)|Abdul Haq]] killed.\n*November 6: Zari, Keshendeh and Aq-Kupruk fall to the Northern Alliance<ref name=\"captured\">Independent Online, [http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?sf=522&set_id=1&click_id=3&art_id=qw1005063841541B226 Taliban commander captured in Rebel victory], November 6, 2001</ref>\n*November 8: [[Pakistan]], being the only nation that still had diplomatic ties to the [[Taliban]], asked [[Afghanistan]]'s rulers to close their [[consulate]] in the city of [[Karachi]].\n*November 9: [[Battle of Mazari Sharif]]. \n*November 10: The Taliban and [[Afghan Northern Alliance|Northern Alliance]] fighters both claimed that the strategic northern Afghan city of [[Mazari Sharif]] was taken by Northern Alliance fighters.\n*November 11: Journalists [[Pierre Billaud]], [[Johanne Sutton]], and [[Volker Handloik]] are ambushed and killed.\n*November 12: [[Taliban]] forces abandon [[Kabul]] ahead of advancing [[Afghan Northern Alliance|Northern Alliance]] troops.\n**[[2001 uprising in Herat]].\n*November 14: Northern Alliance fighters took over [[Kabul]], the Afghan capital, and then controlled virtually all the north of Afghanistan.\n*November 16: [[Mohammed Atef]], the military chief of al-Qaeda, killed in a US airstrike.\n*November 19: Four foreign journalists - [[Harry Burton (journalist)|Harry Burton]], [[Maria Grazia Cutuli]], [[Azizullah Haidari]], and [[Julio Fuentes Serrano|Julio Fuentes]] \u2013 were ambushed and killed.\n*November 25: Northern Alliance gained control of [[Kunduz]], the last Taliban stronghold in Northern Afghanistan, but only after Pakistani aircraft rescue several thousand [[Taliban]] and [[Al-Qaeda]] fighters and their military advisers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hersh |first=Seymour M. |url=http://www.newyorker.com/fact/content/articles/020128fa_FACT |title=Annals of National Security: The Getaway |publisher=The New Yorker |date=2009-01-07 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/news/664935.asp?cp1=1 |title=Breaking News, Weather, Business, Health, Entertainment, Sports, Politics, Travel, Science, Technology, Local, US & World News |publisher=msnbc.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051216152224/http://www.msnbc.com/news/664935.asp?cp1=1 |archivedate=December 16, 2005 }}</ref> The Taliban then controlled less than 25% of the country, mainly around Kandahar in the south.\n**U.S. [[United States Marine Corps|Marine]]s landed in force by [[helicopter]] at [[Camp Rhino]] south of [[Kandahar]] and began preparing it for fixed wing aircraft. They also occupied the main road between Kandahar and Pakistan.\n**[[Battle of Qala-i-Jangi]].  Forces loyal to bin Laden smuggled weapons into their prison near Mazar i Sharif after surrendering at Kunduz. They attacked the Northern Alliance guards and storm an armory. [[U.S. Special Forces]] call in air attacks. Hundreds of prisoners are killed as well as 40 Alliance fighters and one U.S. CIA operative, [[Johnny Michael Spann]]. Spann becomes the first U.S. and Coalition combat casualty. A young American named [[John Walker Lindh]] is found in the midst of the rebellion and extradited to the US on terrorism charges.\n*December 6: [[Kandahar]] falls.\n*December: The [[Battle of Tora Bora]] against Taliban and al-Qaeda fighters; [[Osama bin Laden]] reportedly escapes during this battle.\n*December: The [[Dasht-i-Leili massacre]], where hundreds of Taliban were allegedly suffocated to death while being transported in metal containers.\n*December: The [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)|Bonn Agreement]] establishes the postwar system of government for Afghanistan, and establishes the [[International Security Assistance Force]].\n*December 21: The interim Afghan government is sworn in.\n\n==2002==\n{{main|2002 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*January 4: First US soldier dies due to hostile fire.\n*January 24, the [[Hazar Qadam raid]] sees Americans accidentally attack an allied compound collecting weapons for their Karzai government\n*February 14: [[Abdul Rahman (Afghan minister)|Abdul Rahman]], Afghan Aviation and Tourism Minister, killed by angry Hajj pilgrims.\n*March 1: [[Operation Anaconda]] against al-Qaeda fighters launched.\n*April 17: The 87-year-old exiled king of Afghanistan, [[Mohammed Zahir Shah]], returns.\n*April 18: [[Tarnak Farm incident]] leaves four Canadians dead from [[friendly fire]].\n*June 11: King Zahir Shah opens the first post-Taliban loya jirga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2038399.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Former king urges Afghan unity |publisher=BBC News |date=2002-06-11 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n*July 1: In [[Uruzgan province]], a US [[AC-130 gunship]] struck a wedding party, killing 48 civilians and injuring 117. The United States claimed their plane had come under attack from anti-aircraft fire before the strike.\n*July 6: Vice President [[Abdul Qadir (Afghan leader)|Abdul Qadir]] assassinated in Kabul.\n*September 5: [[2002 Kabul bombing]] kills 30 people.\n\n==2003==\n{{main|2003 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*August 11 \u2013 NATO officially takes command of peacekeeping in Afghanistan.\n*December 14 \u2013 [[2003 loya jirga]] convened to  consider the proposed [[Constitution of Afghanistan|Afghan Constitution]].\n\n==2004==\n{{main|2004 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*January 4 \u2013 Constitution approved by Loya Jirga.\n*January 26 \u2013 Constitution signed by President Hamid Karzai.\n*October 9 \u2013 [[2004 Afghan presidential election]]. In the country\u2019s first direct election, Hamid Karzai wins the presidency with 55.4% of the vote.\n\n==2005==\n{{main|2005 in Afghanistan}}\n\n*June 28: [[Operation Red Wings]] results in the death of 19 Americans and many Taliban fighters.\n*September 18: [[2005 Afghan parliamentary election]].\n\n==2006==\n{{main|2006 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2006}}\n\n*January 13: [[Damadola airstrike]] by US in Pakistan.\n*February 1: The [[Afghanistan Compact]] is developed, establishing a framework of international cooperation with Afghanistan.\n*March 29: [[Battle of Lashkagar]]. Taliban fighters attack a [[NATO]] base.\n*May 15: [[Operation Mountain Thrust]] is launched, the largest offensive since the fall of the Taliban.\n*July: [[Battle of Panjwaii]] between Canadian NATO forces and the Taliban.\n*September 2: Canadians launch [[Operation Medusa]].\n*September 16: [[Operation Mountain Fury]].\n\n==2007==\n{{main|2007 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2007}}\n\n*February 27: [[2007 Bagram Air Base bombing]] during US Vice President [[Dick Cheney]]\u2019s visit.\n*March 4: [[March 4, 2007 Shooting in Shinwar, Afghanistan|Afghan civilians killed by U.S. troops in Shinwar]].\n*March 6: [[Operation Achilles]] against the Taliban in [[Helmand Province]].\n*May 12: Mullah [[Dadullah]] killed.\n*May 13: [[Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan Skirmishes]].\n*June 15: [[Battle of Chora]] begins.\n*June 28: The [[Hyderabad airstrike]] kills a large number of civilians including women and children.\n*July 19: [[2007 South Korean hostage crisis in Afghanistan]] begins.\n*August 16: [[Nangar Khel massacre]] - Eight civilians including a pregnant women and a baby died when Polish  soldiers shelled the village of Nangar Khel. Seven soldiers have been charged with war crimes.\n*November 6: [[2007 Baghlan sugar factory bombing]] kills 75, including six Afghan MPs.\n*December 7: [[Battle of Musa Qala]], a major clash in Helmand Province.\n\n==2008==\n\n{{main|2008 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2008}}\n*January 14: The [[2008 Kabul Serena Hotel attack]] leaves six people dead.\n*February 17: [[2008 Kandahar bombing]] kills 100 people, the deadliest suicide bombing of the war.\n*June 10: [[Gora Prai airstrike]] in Pakistan kills 11 Pakistani paramilitary troops.\n*June 13: [[Sarposa Prison attack]]. Taliban attack the Sarposa Prison, freeing up to 1,000 prisoners.\n*July 6: [[Deh Bala wedding party bombing]]. 47 civilians mostly women and children killed in Nangarhar province.\n*July 7: The [[2008 Indian embassy bombing in Kabul]] kills 58, including four Indians.  India blames Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] for the attack.\n*July 13: [[Battle of Wanat]]. Taliban fighters attack a NATO base, killing nine American soldiers.\n*August 19: The Taliban kill 10 French soldiers in the [[Uzbin valley ambush]].\n*August 22: [[Azizabad airstrike]] kills up to 90 Afghan civilians.\n*August 27: [[Operation Eagle's Summit]] begins in Helmand Province.\n*September: [[United States-Pakistan skirmishes]].\n*September 3: [[Angoor Ada raid]] by US special forces into Pakistan.\n*November 3: [[Wech Baghtu wedding party attack]] kills 37 civilians mostly women and children.\n*December 19: US vows to send 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan.\n\n==2009==\n{{main|2009 in Afghanistan|Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2009}}\n*February 11: [[February 2009 Kabul raids]]\n*May 4: The [[Granai airstrike]] resulted in one of the highest civilian death tolls from Western military action since foreign forces invaded Afghanistan in 2001.\n*July 2: [[Operation Khanjar]] begins\n*September 4: [[2009 Kunduz airstrike|NATO planes attacks two fuel tankers]], which had been hijacked by Taliban insurgents. Up to 142 people died in the attack, including over 100 Afghan civilian victims.<ref name=spiegel-20100806>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,710439,00.html |title=Germany to Pay $500,000 for Civilian Bombing Victims |author=Matthias Gebauer |publisher=Der Spiegel |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=9 August 2010}}</ref>\n*December 1: U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] announces [[Afghanistan War troop surge of 2009]].\n*December 17: [[Operation Septentrion]], assault by 1100 soldiers (mostly French) in the Uzbin Valley.<ref name=\"BBC2009Dec17\">{{cite web |title=French troops spearhead assault in Afghanistan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8419645.stm |work=BBC News |date=2009-12-17 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC2009Dec18\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8419829.stm |title=French Afghan assault concludes |date=2009-12-18 |accessdate=2012-01-21 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=French troops lead Afghan attack on Taliban |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010535631_apeufranceafghanistan.html |date=2009-12-17 |accessdate=2012-01-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100129051149/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2010535631_apeufranceafghanistan.html |archivedate=January 29, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hbKgPKnkMqI0k6GdTP4uP3OTcx9g |author=Karim Talbi |agency=AFP |title=Afghanistan: d\u00e9monstration de force de la L\u00e9gion, cinq Am\u00e9ricains bless\u00e9s |date=2009-12-18 |accessdate=2012-01-21}}</ref>\n*December 29: 10 Afghan civilians mostly school children killed by special operation forces in the botched [[Narang night raid]].\n\n==2010==\n{{main|2010 in Afghanistan}}\n*February 12: Five innocent civilians including two pregnant women and a teenage girl killed in the botched [[Khataba raid]].\n*February 21: [[Uruzgan helicopter attack]] kills 27-33 civilians including four women and a child in Uruzgan province.\n*Spring: Operation Moshtarak Phase I is led by US Marines to retake Marjah, in Helmand Province, from the Taliban.\n*Spring-Summer: U.S. Surge to Afghanistan sees its peak, as 20,000 soldiers are deployed to the south\n*June 23: General [[Stanley A. McChrystal]], commander of the ISAF, resigns after controversial comments critical of the Obama administration were published in a magazine.\n*July 23: The [[Sangin airstrike]] kills a large number of Afghan civilians mostly women and children in Nangarhar province.\n*July 25: [[WikiLeaks]] releases [[Afghan War Diary|90,000 leaked documents]] pertaining to the war in Afghanistan.\n*September 18: Afghan Parliamentary Elections are held, widely criticized as fraudulent, although with notable instances of electoral institution impartiality.\n*Fall: Operation Moshtarak Phases II and III are held in Kandahar, driving the Taliban out of traditional safe-havens\n*Fall: Command of Regional Command South rotates from British to American command.\n\n==2011==\n{{main|2011 in Afghanistan}}\n*January 26: The Afghan National Assembly is inaugurated.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/27/world/asia/27afghan.html?partner=rss&emc=rss After Months of Turmoil, Karzai Opens Parliament]</ref>\n*May 1: The number one Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden is killed by U.S. [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEALs]] in Abbottabad, Pakistan, just miles from [[Islamabad]].\n*May 23: 4 U.S. soldiers (2nd Battalion 27th Infantry Regiment) die and 1 wounded following an improvised explosive device attack in Kunar province.\n*June 4\u20136: The Battle Of Gewi Ridge takes place where a platoon of U.S. soldiers air-assaulted the mountain ridge of Gewi (Kunar province) for over-watch of a major re-supply convoy.  Following the insertion, an intensive firefight lasting 52 hours takes place, resulting in the deaths of 50+ Taliban insurgents.\n*August 6: A [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook|CH-47 Chinook]] helicopter transporting 30 U.S. soldiers (including 17 Navy SEALs), 1 civilian interpreter and 7 Afghan troops is shot down in [[Wardak Province]] by [[rocket-propelled grenade|RPG]]-wielding Taliban insurgents. There were no survivors of the crash. This incident marks the deadliest day for U.S. Forces in Afghanistan since the invasion in 2001.\n*August 11: Vengeance is exacted on the 11 Taliban militants involved in downing the CH-47 Chinook, who are killed in an [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16]] airstrike. Meanwhile, five ISAF service members die following an improvised explosive device attack in the southern provinces.\n*December 9: Mohammed Ishmael, Ghaziabad district (Kunar province) police chief is killed in a suicide bombing of a mosque carried out by a 12-year-old Pakistani boy.\n\n==2012==\n{{main|2012 in Afghanistan}}\n\n==2013==\n{{main|2013 in Afghanistan}}\nThe army of the United States continues to conduct missions throughout Afghanistan, began closing forward operating bases (FOB).\n\n==See also==\n*'''2006:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2006]]\n*'''2007:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2007]]\n*'''2008:''' [[Coalition combat operations in Afghanistan in 2008]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{War in Afghanistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline of the War in Afghanistan (2001-present)}}\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)-related lists]]\n[[Category:Timelines of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|#]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c56:4d08:ddf:5523:23d8:1485:3120", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200e2010)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)"}
{"title_page": "Budtameez", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Budtameez\n| image          = Budtameez.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Manmohan Desai]]\n| producer       = Jagdish Varma\n| writer         = Jwala Mukhi\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Shammi Kapoor]]<br />[[Sadhana Shivdasani|Sadhana]]\n| music          = [[Shankar Jaikishan]]\n| cinematography = Mohan Keshwani\n| editing        = Harish Pathare\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1966\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Budtameez''''' (English: ''Insolent'') is a [[Bollywood films of 1966|1966]] [[Bollywood]] film produced by Jagdish Varma and directed by [[Manmohan Desai]]. The film stars [[Shammi Kapoor]], [[Sadhana Shivdasani|Sadhana]] and [[Manorama (Hindi actress)|Manorama]]. The film's music was by [[Shankar Jaikishan]]. The film was a box office success. It was one of the top grossing movies of 1966.\n\n==Plot==\n\nAfter the passing away of her parents, Shanta lives a wealthy lifestyle in Bombay along with her grandfather, Rajabahadur Murthy Sagar, who is kind-hearted and generous to a fault. Due to his pampering, Shanta has grown up to be headstrong, and rude. In order to teach her a lesson, Rajabahadur appoints Allahabad-based Shyam Kumar Saxena, who turns on his charm, and both fall in love with each other much to the delight of Rajabahadur who quickly arranges their marriage. While Shyam returns home to inform his wheelchair-bound sister, Beena, and widowed stepmother, Rajabahadur and Shanta prepare for the marriage. Then their lives are turned upside down when they receive a wedding invitation announcing the marriage of Shyam with Kamla. The question remains who is Kamla and why is Shyam rejecting Shanta and marrying her?\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shammi Kapoor]] as Shyam Kumar Saxena\n*[[Sadhana Shivdasani]] as Shanta\n*[[Purnima]] as Rita\n*Kamal Mehra as Devdas\n*[[Kanan Kaushal]] credited as Indumati (Paingankar) as Beena (Shyam Kumar Saxena's disabled sister)\n*[[Manorama (Hindi actress)|Manorama]] as Stepmother\n*[[Jagdish Raj]]\n*[[Sunder (actor)|Sunder]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\nMusic of the film was composed by the duo of Shankar Jaikishan and the songs were penned by lyricists Hasrat Jaipuri and Shailendra.\n\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Apni Baahon Se\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Budtameez Kaho Ya Kaho Jaanwar\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Dil Ko Na Mere Tadpao\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Haseen Ho Tum Khuda Nahin Ho\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Sirf Tum Hi To Ho\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]], '''[[Asha Bhosle]]'''\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Surat Haseen Hai Lagta Deewana\"\n| [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Pehla Pehla Pyar\"\n| [[Suman Kalyanpur]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0213532|Budtameez}}\n\n{{Manmohan Desai}}\n\n[[Category:1966 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Shankar Jaikishan]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Manmohan Desai]]\n\n\n{{1960s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Budtameez\n| image          = Budtameez.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Manmohan Desai]]\n| producer       = Jagdish Varma\n| writer         = Jwala Mukhi\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Shammi Kapoor]]<br />[[Sadhana Shivdasani|Sadhana]]\n| music          = [[Shankar Jaikishan]]\n| cinematography = Mohan Keshwani\n| editing        = Harish Pathare\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1966\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Budtameez''''' (English: ''Insolent'') is a [[Bollywood films of 1966|1966]] [[Bollywood]] film produced by Jagdish Varma and directed by [[Manmohan Desai]]. The film stars [[Shammi Kapoor]], [[Sadhana Shivdasani|Sadhana]] and [[Manorama (Hindi actress)|Manorama]]. The film's music was by [[Shankar Jaikishan]]. The film was a box office success. It was one of the top grossing movies of 1966.\n\n==Plot==\n\nAfter the passing away of her parents, Shanta lives a wealthy lifestyle in Bombay along with her grandfather, Rajabahadur Murthy Sagar, who is kind-hearted and generous to a fault. Due to his pampering, Shanta has grown up to be headstrong, and rude. In order to teach her a lesson, Rajabahadur appoints Allahabad-based Shyam Kumar Saxena, who turns on his charm, and both fall in love with each other much to the delight of Rajabahadur who quickly arranges their marriage. While Shyam returns home to inform his wheelchair-bound sister, Beena, and widowed stepmother, Rajabahadur and Shanta prepare for the marriage. Then their lives are turned upside down when they receive a wedding invitation announcing the marriage of Shyam with Kamla. The question remains who is Kamla and why is Shyam rejecting Shanta and marrying her?\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shammi Kapoor]] as Shyam Kumar Saxena\n*[[Sadhana Shivdasani]] as Shanta\n*[[Laxmi Chhaya]] as Rita\n*Kamal Mehra as Devdas\n*[[Kanan Kaushal]] credited as Indumati (Paingankar) as Beena (Shyam Kumar Saxena's disabled sister)\n*[[Manorama (Hindi actress)|Manorama]] as Stepmother\n*[[Jagdish Raj]]\n*[[Sunder (actor)|Sunder]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\nMusic of the film was composed by the duo of Shankar Jaikishan and the songs were penned by lyricists Hasrat Jaipuri and Shailendra.\n\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Apni Baahon Se\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Budtameez Kaho Ya Kaho Jaanwar\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Dil Ko Na Mere Tadpao\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Haseen Ho Tum Khuda Nahin Ho\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Sirf Tum Hi To Ho\"\n| [[Mohammed Rafi]], '''[[Asha Bhosle]]'''\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Surat Haseen Hai Lagta Deewana\"\n| [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Pehla Pehla Pyar\"\n| [[Suman Kalyanpur]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0213532|Budtameez}}\n\n{{Manmohan Desai}}\n\n[[Category:1966 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Shankar Jaikishan]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Manmohan Desai]]\n\n\n{{1960s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Srirangam99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Budtameez"}
{"title_page": "Labor Party (Taiwan)", "text_new": "{{one source|date=August 2017}}\n{{Expand Chinese|\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8 (\u81fa\u7063)|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Labor Party\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-tw|\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8}}}}<br>L\u00e1od\u00f2ng D\u01ceng ([[Taiwanese Mandarin|Mandarin]])<br>L\u00f2-thung T\u00f3ng ([[Taiwanese Hakka|Hakka]])\n| native_name_lang =\n| abbreviation =\n| logo = Labor Party (Taiwan) emblem.svg\n| logo_size = 125px\n| colorcode = Red\n| chairman = Wu Rongyuan\n| deputy_leader =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title = Vice Chairmen\n| leader1_name = Tang Shu<br />Wang Juanping\n| foundation = {{start date|df=y|1989|03|29}}\n| dissolution =\n| ideology = [[Socialism]]<br />[[Chinese reunification]]<br />[[Anti-imperialism]]<br />Anti-[[Taiwan independence]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| headquarters = 6th Floor, No. 25, Lane 344 , Nanjing West Road, [[Datong District, Taipei|Datong District]], [[Taipei]]\n| position = [[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]<ref name=\"Sohu\">{{cite news |title=\u53f0\u6e7e\u52b3\u52a8\u515a\u4e3b\u5e2d\u5434\u8363\u5143\uff1a\u5927\u9646\u5fc5\u987b\u7167\u987e\u53f0\u6e7e\u52b3\u5de5-\u641c\u72d0\u65b0\u95fb |url=http://news.sohu.com/20100302/n270524615.shtml |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=Sohu News |date=2 March 2010 |lang=zh-s}}</ref>\n| religion =\n| international = [[International Communist Seminar]] (until 2014)\n| newspaper =\n| colors =\n| slogan =\n| seats1_title = Local seats\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|2|912|Red}}\n| flag =\n| website = {{URL|http://laborparty.tw/}}\n| country = Taiwan\n}}\n\nThe '''Labor Party''' ({{zh|t=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8|p=L\u00e1od\u00f2ng D\u01ceng|poj=L\u00f4-t\u014dng T\u00f3ng}}) is a [[Socialism|socialist]] [[political party]] in [[Taiwan]], founded on 29 March 1989 by a striking trade union in [[Xinpu]], [[Hsinchu County]]. The party advocates for labor and social reforms and the redistribution of social resources.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web |title=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8\u7c21\u4ecb |url=http://laborparty.tw/node/17 |website=laborparty.tw |publisher=Labor Party (Taiwan) |accessdate=22 April 2020 |lang=zh-s}}</ref> It proposes gradual reunification with [[Mainland China]], with a high level of autonomy reserved for Taiwan under the [[one country, two systems]] principle.<ref name=\"about\"/> Although it is nominally socialist,<ref name=\"about\"/> the party views itself as the ideological successor to the [[Taiwanese Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Sohu\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=\u53f0\u6e7e\u5730\u4e0b\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u5458\u7684\u547d\u8fd0 |url=http://www.gmw.cn/02sz/2001-12/10/14-A9D2F5A290F84B0A48256AD300089675.htm |work=Guangming Daily |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801001737/http://www.gmw.cn/02sz/2001-12/10/14-A9D2F5A290F84B0A48256AD300089675.htm |archivedate=1 August 2012 |lang=zh-s}}</ref>\n\nThe party often assists in unionizing workers, and regularly holds protests against the Taiwanese government's labour policy. In the [[2018 Taiwanese local elections|2018 local elections]], the party won two seats in the [[Hsinchu County Government]], representing the townships of [[Hukou, Hsinchu|Hukou]] and Xinpu.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8\u7576\u90782\u4f4d\u7af9\u7e23\u8b70\u54e1 \u7f85\u7f8e\u6587\u3001\u9673\u65b0\u6e90\u7dad\u7e6b\u53f0\u7063\u5de6\u7ffc\u85aa\u706b |url=https://www.ettoday.net/news/20181124/1315122.htm |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=ETtoday |date=24 November 2018 |language=zh-Hant}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://laborparty.tw/}} {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Taiwanese political parties}}\n\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Labour parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1989]]\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=August 2017}}\n{{Expand Chinese|\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8 (\u81fa\u7063)|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Labor Party\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-tw|\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8}}}}<br>L\u00e1od\u00f2ng D\u01ceng ([[Taiwanese Mandarin|Mandarin]])<br>L\u00f2-thung T\u00f3ng ([[Taiwanese Hakka|Hakka]])\n| native_name_lang =\n| abbreviation =\n| logo = Labor Party (Taiwan) emblem.svg\n| logo_size = 125px\n| colorcode = Red\n| chairman = Wu Rongyuan\n| deputy_leader =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title = Vice Chairmen\n| leader1_name = Tang Shu<br />Wang Juanping\n| foundation = {{start date|df=y|1989|03|29}}\n| dissolution =\n| ideology = [[Socialism]]<br />[[Chinese reunification]]<br />[[Anti-imperialism]]<br />Anti-[[Taiwan independence]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| headquarters = 6th floor, No. 25, Lane 344 , Nanjing West Road, [[Datong District, Taipei|Datong District]], [[Taipei]]\n| position = [[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]<ref name=\"Sohu\">{{cite news |title=\u53f0\u6e7e\u52b3\u52a8\u515a\u4e3b\u5e2d\u5434\u8363\u5143\uff1a\u5927\u9646\u5fc5\u987b\u7167\u987e\u53f0\u6e7e\u52b3\u5de5-\u641c\u72d0\u65b0\u95fb |url=http://news.sohu.com/20100302/n270524615.shtml |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=Sohu News |date=2 March 2010 |lang=zh-s}}</ref>\n| religion =\n| international = [[International Communist Seminar]] (until 2014)\n| newspaper =\n| colors =\n| slogan =\n| seats1_title = Local seats\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|2|912|Red}}\n| flag =\n| website = {{URL|http://laborparty.tw/}}\n| country = Taiwan\n}}\n\nThe '''Labor Party''' ({{zh|t=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8|p=L\u00e1od\u00f2ng D\u01ceng|poj=L\u00f4-t\u014dng T\u00f3ng}}) is a [[Socialism|socialist]] [[political party]] in [[Taiwan]], founded on 29 March 1989 by a striking trade union in [[Xinpu]], [[Hsinchu County]]. The party advocates for labor and social reforms and the redistribution of social resources.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web |title=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8\u7c21\u4ecb |url=http://laborparty.tw/node/17 |website=laborparty.tw |publisher=Labor Party (Taiwan) |accessdate=22 April 2020 |lang=zh-s}}</ref> It proposes gradual reunification with [[Mainland China]], with a high level of autonomy reserved for Taiwan under the [[one country, two systems]] principle.<ref name=\"about\"/> Although it is nominally socialist,<ref name=\"about\"/> the party views itself as the ideological successor to the [[Taiwanese Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Sohu\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=\u53f0\u6e7e\u5730\u4e0b\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u5458\u7684\u547d\u8fd0 |url=http://www.gmw.cn/02sz/2001-12/10/14-A9D2F5A290F84B0A48256AD300089675.htm |work=Guangming Daily |accessdate=21 April 2020 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801001737/http://www.gmw.cn/02sz/2001-12/10/14-A9D2F5A290F84B0A48256AD300089675.htm |archivedate=1 August 2012 |lang=zh-s}}</ref>\n\nThe party often assists in unionizing workers, and regularly holds protests against the Taiwanese government's labour policy. In the [[2018 Taiwanese local elections|2018 local elections]], the party won two seats in the [[Hsinchu County Government]], representing the townships of [[Hukou, Hsinchu|Hukou]] and Xinpu.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8\u7576\u90782\u4f4d\u7af9\u7e23\u8b70\u54e1 \u7f85\u7f8e\u6587\u3001\u9673\u65b0\u6e90\u7dad\u7e6b\u53f0\u7063\u5de6\u7ffc\u85aa\u706b |url=https://www.ettoday.net/news/20181124/1315122.htm |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=ETtoday |date=24 November 2018 |language=zh-Hant}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://laborparty.tw/}} {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Taiwanese political parties}}\n\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Labour parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1989]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_Party_(Taiwan)"}
{"title_page": "Pray for Me (The Weeknd and Kendrick Lamar song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Pray for Me\n| cover      = The Weeknd & Kendrick Lamar - Pray for Me.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Weeknd]] and [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n| album      = [[Black Panther: The Album]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop-rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/kendrick-lamar-pray-for-me-ft-the-weeknd/|title=\"Pray for Me\" [ft. The Weeknd] by Kendrick Lamar / The Weeknd Review|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=March 31, 2018}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=31}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]]|[[Aftermath Entertainment|Aftermath]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]|[[Kendrick Lamar|Kendrick Lamar Duckworth]]|[[Frank Dukes|Adam Feeney]]|[[Jason Quenneville]]|[[Doc McKinney|Martin McKinney]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Doc McKinney]]|[[Frank Dukes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BeqyUJYBrrH/|title=Black Panther OST #prayforme #seasons|via=[[Instagram]]|date=February 1, 2018|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref>}}\n| chronology = [[The Weeknd]]\n| prev_title = [[Secrets (The Weeknd song)|Secrets]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Call Out My Name]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[King's Dead]]\n | prev_year  = 2018\n | title      = Pray for Me\n | year       = 2018\n | next_title = The Mantra\n | next_year  = 2018\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|XR7Ev14vUh8|\"Pray for Me (Lyric Video)\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Pray for Me'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]] and American rapper [[Kendrick Lamar]] from [[Black Panther: The Album|the soundtrack album]] of the [[Marvel Studios]] superhero film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''. The song was released by [[Top Dawg Entertainment]], [[Aftermath Entertainment]], and [[Interscope Records]] on February 2, 2018, as the album's third single. It serves as the second overall collaboration between the two artists.<ref>{{cite web|last=Madden|first=Sidney|title=Kendrick Lamar produced the soundtrack for Black Panther|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/02/02/582641529/kendrick-lamar-and-the-weeknd-team-up-for-pray-for-me|website=npr.org|accessdate=February 2, 2018|date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> The song appears in the movie during the scene where the [[Black Panther (comics)|titular hero]] along with his allies, [[Nakia (comics)|Nakia]] and [[Okoye (comics)|Okoye]], enter a secret casino in [[Busan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/14/17119586/black-panther-paradox-friends-die-hard-bruce-willis|title=Modern culture paradoxes can be explained by a popular Friends question|website=Polygon|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=March 14, 2018|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nThe Weeknd first hinted at his involvement with the ''Black Panther'' soundtrack album with an [[Instagram]] post that he made on January 19, 2018, which contained an illustration of the [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] superhero [[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]] perched on a tree in front of the moon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bonomolo|first=Cameron|title=Kendrick Lamar produced the soundtrack for Black Panther|url=http://comicbook.com/marvel/2018/01/22/the-weeknd-black-panther-kendrick-lamar-album/|website=comicbook.com|accessdate=February 1, 2018|date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> On January 26, 2018, The Weeknd then further hinted at his involvement with the soundtrack when he uploaded an official trailer for the ''Black Panther'' film to his Instagram account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BecHAiPB_Pe/|title=Marvel Studios' Black Panther - War TV Spot|via=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=February 1, 2018|date=January 26, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Then on January 31, 2018, Lamar confirmed The Weeknd's involvement with the soundtrack when he uploaded to his [[Twitter]] account the complete tracklist of the soundtrack, which contained the song \"Pray for Me\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Dumaraog|first=Ana|title=Kendrick Lamar Unveils Black Panther Album Tracklist & Cover Art|url=https://screenrant.com/black-panther-soundtrack-kendrick-lamar/|website=screenrant.com|accessdate=February 1, 2018|date=February 1, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2018, The Weeknd uploaded to his Twitter account a video teasing the release date for \"Pray for Me\" as the soundtrack's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/959222231749373953|title=Pray For Me|via=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=February 1, 2018|date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Pray for Me\" is composed in the key of [[E minor]].<ref>[https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0181846 The Weeknd \"Pray for Me\" Sheet Music]</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAlex Robert Ross of ''[[Noisey]]'' praised the song, calling it \"short, punchy, and self-lacerating.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ross|first1=Alex Robert|title=Kendrick Lamar Teams with The Weeknd on \"Pray for Me\"|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/j5beyd/kendrick-lamar-the-weeknd-release-black-panther-song-pray-for-me|website=[[Noisey]]|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=February 11, 2018|date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Copyright infringement lawsuit==\nIn February 2020, Tesfaye and Lamar were sued by now-split American [[experimental rock]] band [[Yeasayer]] for alleged plagiarism due to vocal similarities with their [[2007 in music|2007]] song \"[[All Hour Cymbals|Sunrise]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berthelot|first1=Th\u00e9au|title=\"Pray for Me\" : Kendrick Lamar et The Weeknd accus\u00e9s de plagiat|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Kendrick-Lamar/news-112973.html|website=Purebreak Charts|accessdate=February 27, 2020|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, the part allegedly stolen from the song includes \"the recording of a distinctive choral performance, which Plaintiffs [Yeasayer] created and recorded using their own voices\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/448660829/Yeasayer-LLC-et-al-v-Tesfaye-et-al|title=Yeasayer, LLC et al v. Tesfaye et al|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Scribd]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/yeasayer-suing-kendrick-lamar-and-the-weeknd-over-black-panther-song/|title=Yeasayer Suing Kendrick Lamar and the Weeknd Over Black Panther Song|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=February 24, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Furthermore, Yeasayer claims that \"Defendants extracted Plaintiffs\u2019 choral performance from a recording of 'Sunrise,' slightly modified it, including, on information and belief, via postprocessing to alter its pitch, among other qualities\" and then subsequently used the modified audio in their own song.<ref name=\":0\" /> The accused party have yet to respond to the accusation.\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits and personnel adapted from digital booklet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Various-artists-black-panther-the-album-booklet-lyrics|title=Various Artists \u2013 Black Panther: The Album [Booklet]|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|accessdate=February 9, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6x6jb9RKo?url=https://genius.com/Various-artists-black-panther-the-album-booklet-lyrics|archive-date=2018-02-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* [[Kendrick Lamar]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, lead vocals\n* [[The Weeknd]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, lead vocals\n* [[Frank Dukes]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Doc McKinney]]&nbsp;\u2013 songwriting, production, recording\n* Beatriz Artola&nbsp;\u2013 recording\n* Shin Kamiyama&nbsp;\u2013 recording\n* Mike Sonier&nbsp;\u2013 recording\n* Barry McCready&nbsp;\u2013 recording assistance\n* [[Jaycen Joshua]]&nbsp;\u2013 mixing\n* David Nakaji&nbsp;\u2013 mixing assistance\n* [[Mike Bozzi]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n* Chris Athens&nbsp;\u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|9|artist=The Weeknd & Kendrick Lamar|song=Pray for Me|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|32|artist=The Weeknd & Kendrick Lamar|song=Pray for Me|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|22|artist=The Weeknd & Kendrick Lamar|song=Pray for Me|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 24, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|39|artist=The Weeknd & Kendrick Lamar|song=Pray for Me|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 3, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|5|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 21, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadachrtop40|1|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadahotac|16|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Colombia ([[National Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-report.com/top-colombia/#tab-1|title=Top 100 Colombia|language=Spanish|publisher=[[National Report]]|accessdate=July 22, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402082728/http://www.national-report.com/top-colombia/|archivedate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| 63\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|57|year=2018|week=10|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|6|artist=The Weeknd & Ke